The machine is self-cleaning and the beer is ready to drink seven days later.

After fermentation, it can be put into casks or bottles and sold directly from a pub, which the company says guarantees its freshness and wipes out transportation costs.

While it costs a considerable amount, the new machine is estimated to cost a quarter of price of setting up a regular £100,000 ($152,000) microbrewery.

Some drinkers may be worried that beer brewed on site is not as uniform as that made at huge breweries, but Robert McLauchlan, director of Brewers World, told MailOnline that the beer is controlled by computer software.

'For the novice brewer we supply ready made ingredients to enable them to ensure repeatability. 

'Unlike large scale breweries the measurements are far more accurate, both for ingredients and for the quantity of water. 

'The system is sealed and so is free from risk of infection. Brews are fresh and so no additives, colouring agents or preservatives are required.

